channel.title: Your Test
channel.description:
Hey guys. How do you guys think about the Your (mine is STAAR test coming up next week/April? Since I'm in 5th grade, it's coming up on Tuesday - Wednesday. When is yours coming and what do yo think about it? My expression:
[img]http://gifsoup.com/view5/2709645/nail-biting-o.gif[/img]

item.title: Your Test
item.dc:creator: @chassy13 Chassy13
item.description:
@chassy13 wrote:

[quote=“Wet Dreamss, post:31, topic:437504”][quote author=Chassy13 link=topic=540209.msg3956081#msg3956081 date=1332772028]
I take my ACT on April 14th. I have to score at least a 22 in Mathematics to avoid a pre-engineering class in college (which consists of Calculus and Analytic Geometry). Otherwise I already am accepted because I’m in the top 15% of my class (requirement is top 50%).

People ahead of me for the 10% of class scholarship are taking idiotic courses like food and low-grade sciences. Next year I’m filling my schedule with mathematics, computer sciences, and AP courses.
[/quote]
Nice! What type of engineering are you looking at getting into?[/quote]

Bachelor’s in Software Engineering for my degree. I’m unsure if I’m going directly into Law Enforcement or Software Engineering out of college. All I have to do to get hired as a police officer would be taking a summer training course. Around my area, police officers are a dime a dozen, so you don’t even need a degree in Law Enforcement to get hired. That way I don’t waste money getting a degree I’m not sure I’ll want my whole life, so I can just switch over to a better paying career.

The type of classes in college for Software Engineering will probably determine what I start out as. I enjoy sitting back and programming, and it would be something I’d enjoy (along with the paycheck!), but also I would enjoy the job of a police officer. I’ve been stuck on the decision for three years now.

One of my brothers-in-law is a Software Engineer, and the other is an Electrical Engineer. The Software Engineer makes around $60,000 annually + any side project profits (an example would be a company that paid him $10,000 to create an iPod application for their company’s usage).
